00:01:39.890 --> 00:01:41.713
- First question is from Marcus.

00:01:43.200 --> 00:01:46.510
Nature recently published a claim

00:01:46.510 --> 00:01:50.723
that humans lived here in
San Diego 130,000 years ago.

00:01:52.730 --> 00:01:53.563
Is there any

00:01:53.563 --> 00:01:56.253
genetic evidence to
support that inference?

00:01:58.939 --> 00:02:00.393
- To my knowledge there is none.

00:02:02.480 --> 00:02:03.313
Where the evidence is,

00:02:03.313 --> 00:02:04.146
is that,

00:02:07.345 --> 00:02:09.440
there were civilizations

00:02:09.440 --> 00:02:12.000
within the Americas, probably,

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:15.380
up to about 16,000 before now,

00:02:15.380 --> 00:02:17.623
not very much earlier than that,

00:02:18.560 --> 00:02:23.560
that those people probably
came on a coastal route,

00:02:23.780 --> 00:02:27.950
from the north, but
there is a lot of debate

00:02:27.950 --> 00:02:32.950
among the Americanologists
about the age at which

00:02:32.950 --> 00:02:36.020
the first settlements in
South America occurred,

00:02:36.020 --> 00:02:40.150
relative to say, Kennecott
Man and Clovis Man,

00:02:40.150 --> 00:02:44.773
which are in the 10 to
13,000 years before now,

00:02:45.740 --> 00:02:49.050
but unlike what happened in Europe,

00:02:49.050 --> 00:02:54.050
or in the Russian area
where Denisovan Man,

00:02:55.640 --> 00:02:58.500
or Denisovans were discovered,

00:02:58.500 --> 00:03:02.630
there is no evidence of any introgression,

00:03:02.630 --> 00:03:06.430
which is sort of a sophisticated
word for hybridization

00:03:06.430 --> 00:03:09.287
with any other people,

00:03:09.287 --> 00:03:13.419
Neanderthals probably
hybridized to some extent

00:03:13.419 --> 00:03:16.733
with modern humans and Denisovan DNA

00:03:17.798 --> 00:03:22.798
which comes from the
Southern Russian area,

00:03:23.550 --> 00:03:28.240
it is found throughout the oceanic area,

00:03:28.240 --> 00:03:31.383
from Southeast Asia towards New Guinea,

00:03:32.589 --> 00:03:34.039
whereas that DNA doesn't seem

00:03:35.363 --> 00:03:37.410
to appear in the European area,

00:03:37.410 --> 00:03:39.480
on the other hand the Neanderthal DNA

00:03:39.480 --> 00:03:44.290
does appear through everywhere
in the western hemisphere,

00:03:44.290 --> 00:03:46.960
except Africa, where there is no evidence

00:03:46.960 --> 00:03:49.170
that there was any hybridization.

00:03:49.170 --> 00:03:53.510
So that's a sort of a
two-minute history of that.

00:03:53.510 --> 00:03:54.958
- Before you leave,

00:03:54.958 --> 00:03:57.203
I have just received this question,

00:03:59.130 --> 00:04:01.853
could the out of Africa
model be overturned some day?

00:04:04.290 --> 00:04:07.150
- I think it's, did everybody hear that?

00:04:07.150 --> 00:04:11.863
It said can the out of Africa
model be overturned one day.

00:04:13.660 --> 00:04:15.913
I think it's highly unlikely,

00:04:16.760 --> 00:04:20.380
there was what was called
the multi-regional hypothesis

00:04:21.791 --> 00:04:24.340
before people started to get significant

00:04:24.340 --> 00:04:27.070
amounts of genetic
information from Africans

00:04:27.070 --> 00:04:30.480
and compare it to the variation

00:04:30.480 --> 00:04:32.750
that existed in the rest of the world,

00:04:32.750 --> 00:04:37.750
there was this hypothesis
from Walpart in Michigan.

00:04:37.980 --> 00:04:39.690
- Walpart.
- Walpart, yeah,

00:04:39.690 --> 00:04:44.690
that humans, hominids evolved several

00:04:44.780 --> 00:04:47.200
times in different places,

00:04:47.200 --> 00:04:49.040
and I think that hypothesis

00:04:49.040 --> 00:04:51.163
has pretty much gone by the board now,

00:04:52.818 --> 00:04:57.120
and acceptance by most paleo archeologists

00:04:57.120 --> 00:05:01.223
is that modern humans exited from Africa,

00:05:02.260 --> 00:05:06.530
whereas probably Homo
Erectus exited a lot earlier,

00:05:06.530 --> 00:05:09.950
so what we talk about,
about out of Africa,

00:05:09.950 --> 00:05:12.700
what I was talking about is
called out of Africa two,

00:05:12.700 --> 00:05:15.610
and out of Africa one is Erectus.

00:05:15.610 --> 00:05:17.800
- Exactly, and before you leave,

00:05:17.800 --> 00:05:21.060
a lot of people present
this as an either or,

00:05:21.060 --> 00:05:25.640
paleontology versus
molecular data, high five.

00:05:25.640 --> 00:05:27.263
Both lines of evidence.

00:05:28.960 --> 00:05:30.643
Now we turn to monkeys.

00:05:31.820 --> 00:05:36.820
Dorothy, is there much theft
of nuts by dominant monkeys,

00:05:37.710 --> 00:05:41.370
or is there sharing between
even unrelated monkeys,

00:05:41.370 --> 00:05:44.490
I ask this as you note the cohesive nature

00:05:44.490 --> 00:05:47.063
of your study group in Brazil.

00:05:48.260 --> 00:05:49.669
- Okay so let's see,
there's two questions,

00:05:49.669 --> 00:05:54.669
do the dominant steal, and is
there sharing among unrelated,

00:05:55.360 --> 00:05:56.610
Right, those are the two?

00:05:58.378 --> 00:06:02.420
So dominants don't steal nuts,

00:06:02.420 --> 00:06:05.610
but they do displace lower ranking

00:06:05.610 --> 00:06:08.050
individuals at anvil sites,

00:06:08.050 --> 00:06:10.820
so the competition that we've seen

00:06:10.820 --> 00:06:13.610
is not about the nut per se,

00:06:13.610 --> 00:06:15.820
but about access to the anvil,

00:06:15.820 --> 00:06:18.610
and particularly access
to that hammer stone,

00:06:18.610 --> 00:06:23.020
the hammer stone is the most uncommon,

00:06:23.020 --> 00:06:26.690
or the least available resource,

00:06:26.690 --> 00:06:29.683
the most valuable resource
because it's rare.

00:06:30.840 --> 00:06:33.840
So I did once see

00:06:33.840 --> 00:06:38.840
a young juvenile steal a nut
that his mother had cracked,

00:06:38.890 --> 00:06:41.940
but that's a different kind of theft,

00:06:41.940 --> 00:06:45.853
and his mother was annoyed,
but nothing much came of it.

00:06:47.410 --> 00:06:49.380
That could be familiar too.

00:06:49.380 --> 00:06:50.450
(audience laughs)

00:06:50.450 --> 00:06:52.510
Let's see the other question was

00:06:53.430 --> 00:06:55.563
Sharing and among unrelated.

00:06:56.450 --> 00:07:00.560
So capuchins are quite tolerant
towards young individuals,

00:07:00.560 --> 00:07:02.150
adult capuchins are quite tolerant

00:07:02.150 --> 00:07:03.160
towards young individuals,

00:07:03.160 --> 00:07:05.933
up to around, somewhere
around two or two and a half,

00:07:07.500 --> 00:07:10.610
and it's quite common for
an adult to crack a nut,

00:07:10.610 --> 00:07:12.060
or to be busy cracking nuts,

00:07:12.060 --> 00:07:13.860
they're often doing this for a while,

00:07:13.860 --> 00:07:15.540
and there's more than
one nut that's cracked,

00:07:15.540 --> 00:07:19.340
and for a whole crowd of
juveniles to be clustered around,

00:07:19.340 --> 00:07:22.810
the pictures I showed often
showed one or two juveniles,

00:07:22.810 --> 00:07:25.100
sometimes it's three or four,

00:07:25.100 --> 00:07:27.500
and they are often sitting so close

00:07:27.500 --> 00:07:29.360
to the adult that is cracking,

00:07:29.360 --> 00:07:30.779
that you have the idea that maybe

00:07:30.779 --> 00:07:34.180
they are gonna get cracked too,

00:07:34.180 --> 00:07:35.380
they don't seem to,

00:07:35.380 --> 00:07:37.520
but they really crowd in closely,

00:07:37.520 --> 00:07:40.230
and the adult just keeps
on doing what it's doing,

00:07:40.230 --> 00:07:42.430
and the young ones are right there,

00:07:42.430 --> 00:07:46.410
and it is not frequent,

00:07:46.410 --> 00:07:50.360
but we have seen an adult allow juveniles

00:07:50.360 --> 00:07:53.110
to simply take nuts from their hands,

00:07:53.110 --> 00:07:55.380
we don't see active giving,

00:07:55.380 --> 00:07:58.280
I saw that once in 15 years of watching,

00:07:58.280 --> 00:08:01.023
I don't know how many
thousands of bouts of cracking,

00:08:02.400 --> 00:08:04.150
and some individuals are more tolerant

00:08:04.150 --> 00:08:06.410
towards the young ones than others,

00:08:06.410 --> 00:08:09.410
and they're kind of preferred
partners for the young ones,

00:08:09.410 --> 00:08:11.760
they kind of hang around
with the nice guys,

00:08:11.760 --> 00:08:15.170
and they are frequently scrounging

00:08:15.170 --> 00:08:18.270
at anvil sites when an
adult has finished and left,

00:08:18.270 --> 00:08:20.720
then there's all kinds of
debris and remains there,

00:08:20.720 --> 00:08:21.890
and that's very attractive

00:08:21.890 --> 00:08:23.330
to the young ones and they go there,

00:08:23.330 --> 00:08:26.000
so there's a lot of you can call it,

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:29.483
post prandial sharing that happens

00:08:29.483 --> 00:08:32.040
at the anvil in this way,

00:08:32.040 --> 00:08:33.870
and a degree of relatedness

00:08:33.870 --> 00:08:36.173
is not particularly important in this,

00:08:37.287 --> 00:08:38.990
in the first place if it's a male

00:08:38.990 --> 00:08:41.700
we aren't certain of
paternity in any case,

00:08:41.700 --> 00:08:43.485
and if it's a female,

00:08:43.485 --> 00:08:47.160
she doesn't seem to mind
if it's her own offspring,

00:08:47.160 --> 00:08:50.380
but typically it is closer relatives

00:08:50.380 --> 00:08:52.230
when it's the female that's cracking.

00:08:54.950 --> 00:08:58.333
- Thank you very much, next
question is for Dietrich,

00:08:59.370 --> 00:09:02.110
and as he comes up here I'll add to it,

00:09:02.110 --> 00:09:05.103
we all saw that picture of the chimpanzee,

00:09:07.462 --> 00:09:10.010
and it was not doing very
well at making stone tools,

00:09:10.010 --> 00:09:11.260
and it didn't have pants.

00:09:15.210 --> 00:09:17.700
How can we suggest evolutionary

00:09:17.700 --> 00:09:20.660
progression of human technology

00:09:20.660 --> 00:09:24.220
when Neolithic technology
appears cross culturally

00:09:24.220 --> 00:09:26.623
and independently across time?

00:09:29.980 --> 00:09:33.970
I can repeat that if you need a minute.

00:09:33.970 --> 00:09:36.480
How can we suggest
evolutionary progression

00:09:36.480 --> 00:09:40.720
of human technology when
the Neolithic technology

00:09:40.720 --> 00:09:44.853
appears cross culturally and
independently across time?

00:09:46.738 --> 00:09:49.263
- Well I don't think I know
a lot about the Neolithic,

00:09:50.155 --> 00:09:51.740
but I wouldn't probably
want to characterize

00:09:51.740 --> 00:09:56.710
there being one unitary
Neolithic technology,

00:09:56.710 --> 00:09:59.830
and I also would hesitate
to use the word progress

00:09:59.830 --> 00:10:02.860
in really any kind of evolution,

00:10:02.860 --> 00:10:05.300
but in terms of technological evolution,

00:10:05.300 --> 00:10:06.650
I think what we see is really

00:10:06.650 --> 00:10:09.950
a diversification in the
paleolithic time period,

00:10:09.950 --> 00:10:14.920
where you have older
technologies sticking around,

00:10:14.920 --> 00:10:19.840
but newer technologies being
added in some places to that.

00:10:19.840 --> 00:10:22.680
Certainly there's a lot of
potential for reinvention,

00:10:22.680 --> 00:10:25.130
again I don't know much about Neolithic,

00:10:25.130 --> 00:10:26.977
but for instance the hand
taxes that I was talking about,

00:10:26.977 --> 00:10:29.110
particularly the earlier ones,

00:10:29.110 --> 00:10:30.000
the early esculapian,

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:31.780
I think it's not unreasonable

00:10:31.780 --> 00:10:34.970
to think that that tool
was invented many times,

00:10:34.970 --> 00:10:36.720
a lot of people think that explains

00:10:36.720 --> 00:10:40.160
some of the geographic
patterning that we do see.

00:10:40.160 --> 00:10:43.630
So I think this cultural accumulation

00:10:43.630 --> 00:10:45.000
and diversification is not

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:48.843
at all incompatible with
multiple reinventions.

00:10:51.980 --> 00:10:52.813
- Thank you.

00:10:54.240 --> 00:10:55.790
My next question indicates

00:10:55.790 --> 00:11:00.300
that the voles and opossums were big hits.

00:11:00.300 --> 00:11:01.663
This one's for Leah.

00:11:03.828 --> 00:11:06.060
It actually is the outline

00:11:06.060 --> 00:11:08.480
of a long-term research project for you,

00:11:08.480 --> 00:11:12.280
so do voles breed fast enough,

00:11:12.280 --> 00:11:16.180
that you could follow multiple
generations of blind voles,

00:11:16.180 --> 00:11:18.200
to see if any permanent evolution

00:11:18.200 --> 00:11:20.450
of brain organization
had occurred over time?

00:11:27.366 --> 00:11:29.840
- I'm not certain I
understand the question, so?

00:11:29.840 --> 00:11:32.503
- I think what they're asking is,

00:11:33.800 --> 00:11:38.800
can you look at the abolition
of the brain in blind voles

00:11:40.320 --> 00:11:44.913
by having multiple generations
in your laboratory,

00:11:44.913 --> 00:11:48.661
given that we all are here on this planet

00:11:48.661 --> 00:11:50.010
for only about a hundred years.

00:11:50.010 --> 00:11:51.750
- Okay, so I'll say two things,

00:11:51.750 --> 00:11:55.602
one is that this might
relate to your question,

00:11:55.602 --> 00:11:58.090
there's actually a natural experiment

00:11:58.090 --> 00:12:00.650
of naturally relatively blind animals,

00:12:00.650 --> 00:12:01.710
they're called blind mole rats,

00:12:01.710 --> 00:12:03.420
and I took them out of my talk,

00:12:03.420 --> 00:12:06.360
because I thought I wasn't
gonna have enough time,

00:12:06.360 --> 00:12:07.780
but it turns out if you have animals

00:12:07.780 --> 00:12:08.690
that are naturally blind,

00:12:08.690 --> 00:12:10.080
you have skin growing over their eyes,

00:12:10.080 --> 00:12:12.040
and their eyes get an ophthalmic,

00:12:12.040 --> 00:12:13.000
really, really tiny,

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:14.250
and they only use their visual

00:12:14.250 --> 00:12:17.087
system for circadian functions,

00:12:17.087 --> 00:12:20.860
night and day, and not object recognition,

00:12:20.860 --> 00:12:22.560
it turns out that if you
look at their neocortex,

00:12:22.560 --> 00:12:25.140
it looks a lot like the
bilateral nucleate voles

00:12:25.140 --> 00:12:27.760
that we made, you can't
get rid of the one,

00:12:27.760 --> 00:12:31.620
but it gets functionally
re-specified to become auditory.

00:12:31.620 --> 00:12:33.550
In terms of voles,

00:12:33.550 --> 00:12:35.240
I'm not thinking they breed fast enough,

00:12:35.240 --> 00:12:37.710
but I think a related question would be,

00:12:37.710 --> 00:12:42.067
what would happen if you looked
at the experimentally blind

00:12:42.067 --> 00:12:46.603
monadelphous that we made,

00:12:47.521 --> 00:12:49.840
and have their mothers reproduce,

00:12:49.840 --> 00:12:54.750
and consistently have the
monadelphous be blind,

00:12:54.750 --> 00:12:58.120
so you're now rearing
this culture of blindness,

00:12:58.120 --> 00:13:00.570
I think you'd probably
see some differences,

00:13:00.570 --> 00:13:03.720
then just the sort of
things that we described,

00:13:03.720 --> 00:13:05.660
so I think that might kind
of answer the question,

00:13:05.660 --> 00:13:07.346
or am I just like blah.

00:13:07.346 --> 00:13:09.249
- Probably how many generations

00:13:09.249 --> 00:13:10.628
of that would you have to run?

00:13:10.628 --> 00:13:12.000
- I don't think it would take very many,

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:13.370
because I will say we did rear

00:13:13.370 --> 00:13:17.162
our blind animals in a
highly enriched environment,

00:13:17.162 --> 00:13:20.280
so we said can we take this
natural somatosensory plasticity

00:13:20.280 --> 00:13:23.550
and amplify and direct it
by rearing these animals

00:13:23.550 --> 00:13:27.463
in a large cage with lots of
different tactical textures,

00:13:27.463 --> 00:13:29.180
and we were able to change
neural response properties,

00:13:29.180 --> 00:13:31.090
we were able to change connectivity,

00:13:31.090 --> 00:13:32.700
we were able to change behavior,

00:13:32.700 --> 00:13:35.470
so that you can actually manipulate things

00:13:35.470 --> 00:13:37.330
beyond just removing sensory activity,

00:13:37.330 --> 00:13:39.857
but changing the environment even further.

00:13:39.857 --> 00:13:41.137
- Very good thank you,

00:13:42.440 --> 00:13:44.403
finally for John Shea,

00:13:45.510 --> 00:13:49.600
I see different people using
a variable amount of tools,

00:13:49.600 --> 00:13:52.330
my sister carries tools and uses them,

00:13:52.330 --> 00:13:54.203
I rarely reach for tools,

00:13:55.320 --> 00:13:59.683
we are the same species
doing different things,

00:14:00.640 --> 00:14:02.740
would your scheme classify us differently?

00:14:09.460 --> 00:14:10.947
- No.

00:14:10.947 --> 00:14:12.350
(audience laughs)

00:14:12.350 --> 00:14:14.210
- Perfect, and I have a follow-up,

00:14:14.210 --> 00:14:16.110
it's not exactly a follow-up.

00:14:16.110 --> 00:14:18.500
Why is fire not considered a tool,

00:14:18.500 --> 00:14:21.310
where does mastery of fire fit
in the history of technology,

00:14:21.310 --> 00:14:25.053
and what impact did it have on
pre-human brain development.

00:14:27.690 --> 00:14:30.020
- That's a bit outside
of my area of expertise,

00:14:30.020 --> 00:14:31.330
I can make fire,

00:14:31.330 --> 00:14:33.100
I enjoy making fire,

00:14:33.100 --> 00:14:36.940
but I'm not an expert on the
development of Pyro technology,

00:14:36.940 --> 00:14:39.460
the earliest claimed evidence of fire

00:14:39.460 --> 00:14:41.736
are between one and a half million

00:14:41.736 --> 00:14:43.360
to a little under one million years ago,

00:14:43.360 --> 00:14:45.570
I think the evidence grows stronger

00:14:45.570 --> 00:14:46.700
in more recent contexts,

00:14:46.700 --> 00:14:47.710
it's a tool,

00:14:47.710 --> 00:14:49.203
it's a physical process,

00:14:50.060 --> 00:14:54.745
but we have such tenuous
and fragile remains of fire,

00:14:54.745 --> 00:14:58.430
it's not as amendable to
describing its variability

00:14:58.430 --> 00:15:00.000
in terms of the traces that remain,

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:02.240
for example, one can
make fire by collision,

00:15:02.240 --> 00:15:03.250
flint and steel,

00:15:03.250 --> 00:15:04.370
friction,

00:15:04.370 --> 00:15:05.640
several different kinds of friction,

00:15:05.640 --> 00:15:06.653
using a lens,

00:15:07.701 --> 00:15:09.640
how you could discriminate

00:15:09.640 --> 00:15:11.710
those various complex
different ways of making fire,

00:15:11.710 --> 00:15:15.080
simply by a pile of carbon stained soil,

00:15:15.080 --> 00:15:17.610
is an unsolvable problem at present.

00:15:17.610 --> 00:15:19.090
How early humans made fire

00:15:19.090 --> 00:15:20.950
is one of the big unanswered questions,

