00:29:59.620 --> 00:30:02.150
So if you look at the
details of the ethnography,

00:30:02.150 --> 00:30:04.330
from either groups in Australia,

00:30:04.330 --> 00:30:06.030
or groups like the Inuit,

00:30:06.030 --> 00:30:09.340
they often have elaborate
cultural technology social norms

00:30:09.340 --> 00:30:11.990
which interconnects these
otherwise disparate groups.

00:30:12.930 --> 00:30:16.760
So things like seal partners,

00:30:16.760 --> 00:30:18.000
so you will have certain individuals

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:19.640
which are gonna share seal meat,

00:30:19.640 --> 00:30:20.710
So when you find a seal you got

00:30:20.710 --> 00:30:22.260
it eventually go find your partner,

00:30:22.260 --> 00:30:23.700
which could be a long trek,

00:30:23.700 --> 00:30:25.640
then you get to interact
in their community.

00:30:25.640 --> 00:30:27.582
Other kinds of long-distance relationships

00:30:27.582 --> 00:30:30.350
keep these lines of communication open.

00:30:30.350 --> 00:30:32.063
We know from the trading
networks in the Inuit

00:30:32.063 --> 00:30:33.720
that they were all interconnected,

00:30:33.720 --> 00:30:36.110
and in fact the languages
were very similar.

00:30:36.110 --> 00:30:38.030
What seems to have happened
prior to the Inuit,

00:30:38.030 --> 00:30:39.390
was a group called the Dorset

00:30:39.390 --> 00:30:41.950
had previously spread
across the Canadian Arctic,

00:30:41.950 --> 00:30:44.770
and they had more complex technology,

00:30:44.770 --> 00:30:46.010
but then over time,

00:30:46.010 --> 00:30:46.890
they broke apart and they

00:30:46.890 --> 00:30:48.800
became more technologically isolated,

00:30:48.800 --> 00:30:50.490
and then they lost bows and arrows,

00:30:50.490 --> 00:30:51.630
which was a big trouble for them

00:30:51.630 --> 00:30:54.005
when the Inuit arrived
with bows and arrows.

00:30:54.005 --> 00:30:58.058
And another example from
