00:31:45.735 --> 00:31:47.135
- Okay we'll look for those.

00:31:48.300 --> 00:31:52.550
So then the observation is that there are

00:31:52.550 --> 00:31:55.690
of course these wonderful
social insects like termites

00:31:55.690 --> 00:31:58.310
who have a kind of collective brain,

00:31:58.310 --> 00:32:01.620
so is there a strong or a weak analogy

00:32:01.620 --> 00:32:03.200
between the collective brain

00:32:03.200 --> 00:32:05.500
for hominids that you are thinking about,

00:32:05.500 --> 00:32:07.943
and the collective brain for termites?

00:32:09.660 --> 00:32:11.160
- So I think the best work on

00:32:11.160 --> 00:32:14.480
this is by a biologist named Tom Seeley,

00:32:14.480 --> 00:32:16.470
and he has a book called
Wisdom of the Hive,

00:32:16.470 --> 00:32:20.470
and he actually discusses how
bees make communal decisions,

00:32:20.470 --> 00:32:22.630
by all the bees go out
to their different areas

00:32:22.630 --> 00:32:23.900
and they come back together,

00:32:23.900 --> 00:32:25.390
and they can do these waggle dances

00:32:25.390 --> 00:32:27.400
which is a way of
aggregating the information,

00:32:27.400 --> 00:32:30.180
until one signal wins out,

00:32:30.180 --> 00:32:31.700
and then they all go that way.

00:32:31.700 --> 00:32:35.390
So there are parallel
patterns in other species,

00:32:35.390 --> 00:32:36.990
where information is aggregated,

00:32:36.990 --> 00:32:39.740
and the group functions as
a kind of collective brain.

00:32:39.740 --> 00:32:40.600
In the case of humans,

00:32:40.600 --> 00:32:42.140
ours is just a more powerful system,

00:32:42.140 --> 00:32:44.380
because with cultural learning

00:32:44.380 --> 00:32:45.310
we can communicate

00:32:45.310 --> 00:32:47.260
so many different kinds of information.

00:32:48.680 --> 00:32:52.550
- Okay, and what were the genetic changes

00:32:52.550 --> 00:32:55.510
that occurred about two
million years ago such

00:32:55.510 --> 00:32:57.070
that hominids gathered

00:32:57.070 --> 00:33:00.223
in larger groups that
made all of this happen?

00:33:03.180 --> 00:33:06.460
- So the case that I make in
The Secret of Our Success,

00:33:06.460 --> 00:33:07.930
is that the changes weren't genetic,

00:33:07.930 --> 00:33:11.850
so I don't like genetic
magic bullet explanations,

00:33:11.850 --> 00:33:14.290
so I proposed one thing

00:33:14.290 --> 00:33:16.870
is that there was a larger predator guild,

00:33:16.870 --> 00:33:19.970
and one of the ways mammals
respond to more predators,

00:33:19.970 --> 00:33:21.430
is they cluster in larger groups,

00:33:21.430 --> 00:33:23.580
so if we had a Savannah bipedal ape,

00:33:23.580 --> 00:33:24.880
it would cluster in larger group,

00:33:24.880 --> 00:33:26.500
with a larger predator guild.

00:33:26.500 --> 00:33:28.640
At the same time the environmental

00:33:28.640 --> 00:33:30.670
fluctuations began to increase,

00:33:30.670 --> 00:33:33.110
so we now know this from
these deep lake cores,

00:33:33.110 --> 00:33:34.960
that showed you were
getting more fluctuation,

00:33:34.960 --> 00:33:36.080
and theoretical work done

00:33:36.080 --> 00:33:38.388
by Rob Boyd and Pete Richardson,

00:33:38.388 --> 00:33:39.859
indicates that we should expect

00:33:39.859 --> 00:33:41.700
more reliance on social learning

00:33:41.700 --> 00:33:44.010
when you see the environmental change.

00:33:44.010 --> 00:33:45.740
So those are two key factors

00:33:45.740 --> 00:33:47.090
that don't have anything to do with genes

00:33:47.090 --> 00:33:48.760
That would have meant that primates

00:33:48.760 --> 00:33:50.160
were more likely to cross.

00:33:50.160 --> 00:33:50.993
